  "text": "In the present study we investigated the effects of OM pulses on SR, benthic metabolism, and Fe-sulfide dynamics in sediment mesocosms with indigenous populations of infauna. Two types of organically poor sediments, differing mainly in Fe content, were exposed to weekly pulses of OM for 9 wk. Benthic metabolism was determined as the sediment -water exchange of total CO 2 (TCO 2 = CO 2 + H 2 CO 3 + HCO 3 -+ CO 3 , and TH 2 S. SR was measured by radiotracer measurements, and small-scale spatial and temporal changes in sulfide accumulation were determined by microelectrodes. Fe and S budgets provided the basis for estimates of iron-driven sulfide buffering as well as rates of sulfide oxidation and TRIS formation. C and N budgets provided evidence for the efficiency of OM degradation at the sediment -water interface. Furthermore, by comparison with [CITATION_1] , we draw conclusions about the impact of infauna on S, C, and N cycling in organically enriched sediments.",
